    explanation: "Argument Evaluation\n\nSituation: Candle Corporation's television stations are likely to have more income from advertisers because the number and percentage of viewers aged 18 to 49 is increasing, and advertisers prefer to reach this age group.\n\nReasoning: What would most strengthen the argument? The argument assumes that because Candle has more viewers in the preferred demographic, advertisers will pay more. To strengthen this, we need evidence that advertisers actually act on their preference for the 18-49 age group by directing their advertising spending toward channels that reach this demographic.\n\nA. Correct. If advertisers carefully monitor demographic characteristics and purchase advertising time to reach their preferred audiences, then they will indeed direct more advertising spending toward Candle stations as those stations increasingly reach the 18-49 demographic. This directly supports the conclusion that Candle will receive more income from advertisers.\n\nB. This suggests Candle viewers over 49 buy fewer advertised products than other stations' viewers over 49, which would weaken rather than strengthen the argument.\n\nC. More ads directed at viewers over 49 doesn't strengthen the claim that Candle will get more income based on its growing 18-49 audience.\n\nD. Showing reruns when competitors show original programming might actually reduce viewership and advertising revenue.\n\nE. Disposable income levels don't directly address whether advertisers will pay Candle more for reaching the 18-49 demographic.\n\nThe correct answer is A.",
